Approach 1: List (We can sort both ascending and descending order for both Premitive and non premitive data types)
String[] names={"Apple", "Cake", "Banana"};
int[] nums={5, 3, 2, 1};

->Create one List
List<String> myList=new ArrayList<String>();
List<Integer> myList1=new ArrayList<Integer>();

->Use the sort() and reverseOrder() methods

Approach 2: Use Arrays class
->Non Primitive: String, Integer...will work both ascending and descending order
->Primitive: int, char, float..will work for only ascending order

String[] names={"Apple", "Cake", "Banana"};

Arrays.sort(names); //ascending order

Arrays.sort(names, Collections.reverseOrder()); //descending order

int[] nums={5, 3, 2, 1};

Arrays.sort(nums); //ascending order

Arrays.sort(nums, Collections.reverseOrder()); //descending order not working

we have to change the position of the array


List<String> myList=new ArrayList<String>();
List<Integer> myList1=new ArrayList<Integer>();

->Use the sort() and reverseOrder() methods


Store String array in List and then